paragraphs.name: 0af9
paragraphs.text: Introversion/extroversion is often presented as a binary dichotomy. In fact, most of us are likely ambiverts — people with the ability to switch modes. Yes, some people are naturally more outgoing than others, but most of us can cultivate the ability to find what mode best suits the situation at hand.

paragraphs.name: 736c
paragraphs.text: I embraced being introverted at a young age. I often noticed the popular, more socially skilled extroverts, when by themselves, seemed lost and very unsure of themselves. I was always (and still am to this day) fine with being alone. Over the years I’ve developed enough social skills to fit in with a variety of social situations, but I continue to value time to myself — just to think or create.

paragraphs.text: I wanted to be one of the naturals—one of those kids with a lot of friends that ruled the schoolyard with an easy social grace. Each time I fumbled in front of a girl, each time I ate alone in the cafeteria, I hated myself a bit more.

paragraphs.name: 63a1
paragraphs.text: George Washington, of course, was hyper-introverted. Churchill? Introvert. (He drank a hell of a lot when around people.) Hamilton? Introvert. Napoleon? Introvert. Tokugawa? Introvert.
Oh, I thought. I’ve been playing mental chess all my life.

I wanted to be one of the naturals—one of those kids with a lot of friends that ruled the schoolyard with an easy social grace. Each time I fumbled in front of a girl, each time I ate alone in the cafeteria, I hated myself a bit more.

paragraphs.name: a360
paragraphs.text: “It seems much easier for introverts to learn how to navigate the social and political worlds than for extroverts to learn how to be alone and reflective without going insane. And being able to be reflective — to self-modify, study, analyze, synthesize — is probably the master meta-skill for nearly all of thriving at life.”

paragraphs.name: 05fa
paragraphs.text: Ten years ago, if you had asked me if I wanted to be born again as an extrovert, it would have been an easy yes.
“Shyness is the fear of social disapproval or humiliation, while introversion is a preference for environments that are not overstimulating. Shyness is inherently painful; introversion is not.”
